\v 38 Then you are not the Egyptian who before these days raised a revolt and led out into the wilderness the four thousand men of the Assassins?”\f + \fr 21:38 \ft Also known as the “Sicarii” from the Latin word “sicarius” = dagger, after the short dagger used to assassinate political opponents \f* 
\v 39 But Paul said, “I am a Jewish man from Tarsus in Cilicia, a citizen of no unimportant city. Now I ask you, allow me to speak to the people.” 
\v 40 So \add when\add*\ef + \fr 21:40 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“permitted”) \ef* he permitted \add him\add*,\ef + \fr 21:40 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* Paul, standing there on the steps, motioned with \add his\add*\ef + \fr 21:40 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* hand to the people. And \add when there\add*\ef + \fr 21:40 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“was”) \ef* was a great silence, he addressed \add them\add*\ef + \fr 21:40 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* in the Aramaic language, saying,
\c 22
\p 
\v 1  “Men—brothers and fathers—listen to my defense to you now!” 
\v 2 And \add when they\add*\ef + \fr 22:2 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“heard”) which is understood as temporal \ef* heard that he was addressing them in the Aramaic language, ⸤they became even more silent⸥.\f + \fr 22:2 \ft Literally “they showed even more silence” \f* And he said, 
\v 3 “I am a Jewish man born in Tarsus in Cilicia, but brought up in this city at the feet of Gamaliel, educated according to the exactness of the law received from our fathers, being zealous for God, just as all \add of\add* you are today. 
\v 4 ⸤I⸥\f + \fr 22:4 \ft Literally “who” \f* persecuted this Way to the death, tying up and delivering to prison both men and women, 
\v 5 as indeed the high priest and the whole council of elders can testify about me, from whom also I received letters to the brothers in Damascus, \add and\add*\ef + \fr 22:5 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“received”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* was traveling \add there\add*\ef + \fr 22:5 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* to lead away those who were there also tied up to Jerusalem so that they could be punished.
\s1 Paul Tells of His Conversion on the Damascus Road
\m 
\v 6 “And it happened that \add as\add*\ef + \fr 22:6 \ft ﻿*Here “\add as\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“was traveling”) which is understood as temporal \ef* I was traveling and approaching Damascus around noon, suddenly a very bright light from heaven flashed around me, 
\v 7 and I fell to the ground and heard a voice saying to me, ‘Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me?’ 
\v 8 And I answered, ‘Who are you, Lord?’ And he said to me, ‘I am Jesus the Nazarene whom you are persecuting.’ 
\v 9 (Now those who were with me saw the light but did not hear the voice of the one who was speaking to me.) 
\v 10 So I said, ‘What should I do, Lord?’ And the Lord said to me, ‘Get up \add and\add*\ef + \fr 22:10 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“get up”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* proceed to Damascus, and there it will be told to you about all \add the things\add* that have been appointed for you to do.’ 
\v 11 And as I could not see as a result of the brightness of that light, I arrived in Damascus led by the hand of those who were with me. 
\v 12 And a certain Ananias, a devout man according to the law, well spoken of by all the Jews who live \add there\add*, 
\v 13 came to me and stood by \add me\add*\ef + \fr 22:13 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* \add and\add*\ef + \fr 22:13 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“stood by”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* said to me, ‘Brother Saul, regain \add your\add* sight!’ And \add at that\add* same time I looked up at him \add and saw him\add*.\ef + \fr 22:13 \ft *The words “\add and saw him\add*” are not in the Greek text but are supplied in the translation for clarity \ef* 
\v 14 And he said, ‘The God of our fathers has appointed you to know his will, and to see the Righteous One and to hear a voice from his mouth, 
\v 15 because you will be a witness for him\f + \fr 22:15 \ft Or “to him” \f* to all people of what you have seen and heard. 
\v 16 And now why are you delaying? Get up, be baptized, and wash away your sins, calling on his name!’
\p 
\v 17 “And it happened that \add when\add*\ef + \fr 22:17 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“returned”) which is understood as temporal \ef* I returned to Jerusalem and I was praying in the temple courts,\ef + \fr 22:17 \ft *Here “\add courts\add*” is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself \ef* I was in a trance, 
\v 18 and saw him saying to me, ‘Hurry and depart ⸤quickly⸥\f + \fr 22:18 \ft Literally “with quickness” \f* from Jerusalem, because they will not accept your testimony about me.’ 
\v 19 And I said, ‘Lord, they themselves know that from synagogue \add to synagogue\add* I was imprisoning and beating those who believed in you. 
\v 20 And when the blood of your witness Stephen was being shed, I myself also was standing near and was approving, and was guarding the cloaks of those who were killing him.’ 
\v 21 And he said to me, ‘Go, because I will send you far away to the Gentiles!’ ”
\s1 Paul Questioned by the Military Tribune
\m 
\v 22 Now they were listening to him until this word, and they raised their voices, saying, “Away with such a man from the earth! For it is not fitting \add for\add* him to live!” 
\v 23 And \add while\add*\ef + \fr 22:23 \ft ﻿*Here “\add while\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“were screaming”) \ef* they were screaming and throwing off \add their\add*\ef + \fr 22:23 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* cloaks and throwing dust into the air, 
\v 24 the military tribune ordered him to be brought into the barracks,\f + \fr 22:24 \ft Or “headquarters” \f* saying he was to be examined with a lash so that he could find out for what reason they were crying out against him in this way. 
\v 25 But when they had stretched him out for the lash,\f + \fr 22:25 \ft Or “with straps” (in order to lash him) \f* Paul said to the centurion standing there, “Is it permitted for you to flog a man \add who is\add* a Roman citizen and uncondemned?” 
\v 26 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 22:26 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“heard”) which is understood as temporal \ef* the centurion heard \add this\add*,\ef + \fr 22:26 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* he went to the military tribune \add and\add*\ef + \fr 22:26 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“went to”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* reported \add it\add*,\ef + \fr 22:26 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* saying, “What are you about to do? For this man is a Roman citizen!” 
\v 27 So the military tribune came \add and\add*\ef + \fr 22:27 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“came”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* said to him, “Tell me, are you a Roman citizen?” And he said, “Yes.” 
\v 28 And the military tribune replied, “I acquired this citizenship for a large sum of money.” And Paul said, “But I indeed was born \add a citizen\add*.\ef + \fr 22:28 \ft *The words “\add a citizen\add*” are not in the Greek text but are implied \ef* 
\v 29 Then immediately those who were about to examine him kept away from him, and the military tribune also was afraid \add when he\add*\ef + \fr 22:29 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“realized”) which is understood as temporal \ef* realized that he was a Roman citizen and that ⸤he had tied him up⸥.\f + \fr 22:29 \ft Literally “he was having tied him up” \f* 
\v 30 But on the next day, \add because he\add*\ef + \fr 22:30 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“wanted”) which is understood as causal \ef* wanted to know the true \add reason\add* why he was being accused by the Jews, he released him and ordered the chief priests and the whole Sanhedrin to assemble, and he brought down Paul \add and\add*\ef + \fr 22:30 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“brought down”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* had \add him\add*\ef + \fr 22:30 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* stand before them.
\c 23
\s1 Paul Before the Sanhedrin
\m 
\v 1  And looking intently at the Sanhedrin, Paul said, “Men \add and\add* brothers, I have lived my life in all good conscience before God to this day.” 
\v 2 So the high priest Ananias ordered those standing near him to strike his mouth. 
\v 3 Then Paul said to him, “God is going to strike you, \add you\add* whitewashed wall! And are you sitting \add there\add* judging me according to the law, and acting contrary to the law do you order me to be struck?” 
\v 4 And those who stood nearby said, “Are you reviling the high priest of God?” 
\v 5 And Paul said, “I did not know, brothers, that he was high priest. For it is written, ‘You must not speak evil \add of\add* a ruler of your people.’ ”\f + \fr 23:5 \ft A quotation from \xt Exod 22:28 \ft \f*
\p 
\v 6 Now \add when\add*\ef + \fr 23:6 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“realized”) which is understood as temporal \ef* Paul realized that one part were Sadducees and the other Pharisees, he shouted out in the Sanhedrin, “Men \add and\add* brothers! I am a Pharisee, a son of Pharisees! I am being judged concerning the hope and the resurrection of the dead!” 
\v 7 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 23:7 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“said”) \ef* he said this, a dispute developed between the Pharisees and Sadducees, and the assembly was divided. 
\v 8 (For the Sadducees say there is no resurrection or angel or spirit, but the Pharisees acknowledge \add them\add* all.) 
\v 9 And there was loud shouting, and some of the scribes from the party of the Pharisees stood up \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:9 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“stood up”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* contended sharply, saying, “We find nothing wrong with this man! But \add what\add* if a spirit or an angel has spoken to him?” 
\v 10 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 23:10 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“became”) \ef* the dispute became severe, the military tribune, fearing lest Paul be torn apart by them, ordered the detachment to go down, take him away from their midst, and bring \add him\add*\ef + \fr 23:10 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* into the barracks.\f + \fr 23:10 \ft Or “headquarters” \f* 
\v 11 And the next night the Lord stood by him \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:11 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“stood by”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* said, “Have courage, for as you have testified about me in Jerusalem, so you must also testify in Rome.”
\s1 A Conspiracy to Kill Paul
\m 
\v 12 And \add when it\add*\ef + \fr 23:12 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“was”) \ef* was day, the Jews made a conspiracy \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:12 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“made”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* bound themselves under a curse, saying \add they would\add*\f + \fr 23:12 \ft Literally “saying neither to eat nor to drink”; the words “they would” are supplied for smoother English style \f* neither eat nor drink until they had killed Paul. 
\v 13 Now there were more \add than\add* forty who had made this conspiracy, 
\v 14 who went to the chief priests and the elders \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:14 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“went to”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* said, “We have bound ourselves under a curse to partake of nothing until we have killed Paul. 
\v 15 Therefore, now you along with the Sanhedrin explain to the military tribune that he should bring him down to you, as \add if you\add* were going to determine more accurately the things concerning him. And we are ready to do away with him before he comes near.”
\p 
\v 16 But \add when\add*\ef + \fr 23:16 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“heard about”) which is understood as temporal \ef* the son of Paul’s sister heard about the ambush, he came and entered into the barracks\f + \fr 23:16 \ft Or “headquarters” \f* \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:16 \ft ﻿*Here “and” is supplied because the two previous participles (“came” and “entered”) have been translated as finite verbs \ef* reported \add it\add*\ef + \fr 23:16 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* to Paul. 
\v 17 So Paul called one of the centurions \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:17 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“called”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* said, “Bring this young man to the military tribune, because he has something to report to him.” 
\v 18 So he took him \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:18 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“took”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* brought \add him\add*\ef + \fr 23:18 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* to the military tribune and said, “The prisoner Paul called me \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:18 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“called”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* asked \add me\add*\ef + \fr 23:18 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* to bring this young man to you \add because he\add*\ef + \fr 23:18 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“has”) which is understood as causal \ef* has something to tell you.” 
\v 19 And the military tribune, taking hold of his hand and withdrawing privately, asked, “What is it that you have to report to me?” 
\v 20 And he said, “The Jews have agreed to ask you that you bring Paul down to the Sanhedrin tomorrow, as \add if they\add* were going to inquire somewhat more accurately concerning him. 
\v 21 You therefore do not be persuaded by them, because more \add than\add* forty men of ⸤their number⸥\f + \fr 23:21 \ft Literally “them” \f* are lying in wait \add for\add* him, who have bound themselves under a curse neither to eat nor to drink until they have done away with him. And now they are ready, waiting for ⸤you to agree⸥.”\f + \fr 23:21 \ft Literally “the assurance of agreement from you” \f* 
\v 22 So the military tribune sent the young man away, directing \add him\add*,\ef + \fr 23:22 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* “Tell no one that you have revealed these \add things\add* to me.”
\p 
\v 23 And he summoned two of the centurions \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:23 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“summoned”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* said, “Make ready from the third hour of the night two hundred soldiers and seventy horsemen and two hundred spearmen,\f + \fr 23:23 \ft A word of uncertain meaning, probably a military technical term \f* in order that they may proceed as far as Caesarea. 
\v 24 And provide mounts so that they can put Paul on them \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:24 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“put … on”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* bring \add him\add*\ef + \fr 23:24 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* safely to Felix the governor.” 
\v 25 ⸤He wrote⸥\f + \fr 23:25 \ft Literally “writing” \f* a letter that had this form:\f + \fr 23:25 \ft Or “content” \f*
\p 
\v 26 Claudius Lysias.
\p To his excellency Governor Felix.
\m1 Greetings!
\p1 
\v 27 This man was seized by the Jews and was about to be killed by them \add when I\add*\ef + \fr 23:27 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“came upon”) which is understood as temporal \ef* came upon \add them\add*\ef + \fr 23:27 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* with the detachment \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:27 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“came upon”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* rescued \add him\add*,\ef + \fr 23:27 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* \add because I\add*\ef + \fr 23:27 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“learned”) which is understood as causal \ef* learned that he was a Roman citizen. 
\v 28 And \add because I\add*\ef + \fr 23:28 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“wanted”) which is understood as causal \ef* wanted to know the charge for which they were accusing him, I brought \add him\add*\ef + \fr 23:28 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* down to their Sanhedrin.\f + \fr 23:28 \ft Or “council” \f* 
\v 29 I found ⸤he⸥\f + \fr 23:29 \ft Literally “whom” \f* was accused concerning controversial questions of their law, but having no charge deserving death or imprisonment. 
\v 30 And \add when it\add*\ef + \fr 23:30 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“was made known”) which is understood as temporal \ef* was made known to me there would be a plot against the man, I sent \add him\add*\ef + \fr 23:30 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* to you immediately, also ordering \add his\add*\ef + \fr 23:30 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* accusers to speak against him\f + \fr 23:30 \ft Some manuscripts have “to state the charges against him” (literally, “to speak the \fq things \ft against him”) \f* before you.
\p 
\v 31 Therefore the soldiers, in accordance with ⸤their orders⸥,\f + \fr 23:31 \ft Literally “what was ordered to them” \f* took Paul \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:31 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“took”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* brought \add him\add*\ef + \fr 23:31 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* to Antipatris during the night. 
\v 32 And on the next day they let the horsemen go on with him, \add and\add*\ef + \fr 23:32 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“let”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* they returned to the barracks.\f + \fr 23:32 \ft Or “headquarters” \f* 
\v 33 ⸤The horsemen⸥,\f + \fr 23:33 \ft Literally “who” \f* \add when they\add*\ef + \fr 23:33 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“came”) which is understood as temporal \ef* came to Caesarea and delivered the letter to the governor, also presented Paul to him. 
\v 34 So \add after\add*\ef + \fr 23:34 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“reading”) which is understood as temporal \ef* reading \add the letter\add*\ef + \fr 23:34 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* and asking what province he was from, and learning that \add he was\add* from Cilicia, 
\v 35 he said, “I will give you a hearing whenever your accusers arrive also,” giving orders \add for\add* him to be guarded in the praetorium\f + \fr 23:35 \ft The “praetorium” of Herod refers to the palace of Herod the Great in Caesarea Maritima \f* of Herod.
\c 24
\s1 Paul Before Felix at Caesarea Maritima
\m 
\v 1  And after five days the high priest Ananias came down with some elders and an attorney, a certain Tertullus, all of whom brought charges against Paul to the governor. 
\v 2 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 24:2 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“had been summoned”) \ef* he had been summoned, Tertullus began to accuse \add him\add*,\ef + \fr 24:2 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* saying, “We have experienced\ef + \fr 24:2 \ft ﻿*Here this participle (“have experienced”) and the following participle (“are taking place”) have been translated as finite verbs in keeping with English style \ef* much\f + \fr 24:2 \ft Or “many \fq years \ft ,” with “years” understood \f* peace through you, and reforms are taking place in this nation through your foresight. 
\v 3 Both in every \add way\add* and everywhere we acknowledge \add this\add*,\ef + \fr 24:3 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* most excellent Felix, with all gratitude. 
\v 4 But so that I may not impose on you for longer, I implore you to hear us briefly with your \add customary\add* graciousness. 
\v 5 For we have found\ef + \fr 24:5 \ft ﻿*Here this participle (“found”) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style \ef* this man \add to be\add* a public menace and one who causes riots among all the Jews throughout the Roman Empire\f + \fr 24:5 \ft Literally “the inhabited earth,” but here this is probably rhetorical hyperbole for the Roman Empire, especially since Felix, the Roman governor, is being addressed \f* and a ringleader of the sect of the Nazarenes, 
\v 6 who even attempted to desecrate the temple, and we arrested ⸤him\f + \fr 24:6 \ft Literally “whom” \f*﻿⸥.\f + \fr 24:6 \ft Some later manuscripts include the following additional material between v. \xt 6 \ft and v. \xt 8 \ft : “and we wanted to judge him according to our law, (24:7) but Lysius the military tribune came and took him from our hands with much violence, (24:8) ordering his accusers to come before you.” \f* 
\v 8 \add When\add*\ef + \fr 24:8 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“examine”) which is understood as temporal \ef* you yourself examine \add him\add*\ef + \fr 24:8 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* you will be able to find out from ⸤him⸥\f + \fr 24:8 \ft Literally “whom” \f* about all these \add things\add* of which we are accusing him.” 
\v 9 And the Jews also joined in the attack, asserting these \add things\add* were so.
\p 
\v 10 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 24:10 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“gestured”) \ef* the governor gestured for him to speak, Paul replied, “\add Because I\add*\ef + \fr 24:10 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“know”) which is understood as causal \ef* know you have been a judge over this nation for many years, I defend myself cheerfully \add with respect to\add* the things concerning myself. 
\v 11 You can ascertain that ⸤it has not been more than⸥\f + \fr 24:11 \ft Literally “there are not to me more than” \f* twelve days ⸤since⸥\f + \fr 24:11 \ft Literally “from which \fq time \ft ” \f* I went up to Jerusalem to worship. 
\v 12 And neither did they find me arguing with anyone or making a crowd develop in the temple \add courts\add*\ef + \fr 24:12 \ft ﻿*Here “\add courts\add*” is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself \ef* nor in the synagogues nor throughout the city. 
\v 13 Nor can they prove \add the things\add*\ef + \fr 24:13 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* to you concerning which they are now accusing me. 
\v 14 But I do confess this to you, that according to the Way (which they call a sect), so I worship the God of our fathers, believing all things \add that are\add* in accordance with the law and that are written in the prophets, 
\v 15 having a hope in God which these \add men\add* also themselves await: \add that\add* there is going to be a resurrection of both the righteous and the unrighteous. 
\v 16 ⸤For this reason⸥\f + \fr 24:16 \ft Literally “by this” \f* also \add I\add* myself ⸤always⸥\f + \fr 24:16 \ft Literally “through everything” \f* do my best to have a clear conscience toward God and people. 
\v 17 So after many years, I came to practice charitable giving and offerings to my people,\f + \fr 24:17 \ft Or “nation” \f* 
\v 18 in which they found me purified in the temple \add courts\add*,\ef + \fr 24:18 \ft *Here “\add courts\add*” is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself \ef* not with a crowd or with a disturbance. 
\v 19 But \add there are\add* some Jews from Asia\f + \fr 24:19 \ft A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor) \f* who ought to be present before you and bring charges against \add me\add*,\ef + \fr 24:19 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* if they have anything against me, 
\v 20 or these \add men\add* themselves should say what crime they found \add when\add*\ef + \fr 24:20 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“stood”) \ef* I stood before the Sanhedrin,\f + \fr 24:20 \ft Or “council” \f* 
\v 21 other than concerning this one declaration that I shouted \add while\add*\ef + \fr 24:21 \ft ﻿*Here “\add while\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“standing there”) which is understood as temporal \ef* standing there before them: ‘I am being judged before you today concerning the resurrection of the dead!’ ”
\s1 Paul Held Awaiting Trial
\m 
\v 22 But Felix, \add because he\add*\ef + \fr 24:22 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“understood”) which is understood as causal \ef* understood the \add facts\add* concerning the Way more accurately, put them off, saying, “When Lysias the military tribune comes down, I will decide ⸤your case⸥.”\f + \fr 24:22 \ft Literally “the \fq case \ft with respect to you” \f* 
\v 23 \add He\add* ordered\ef + \fr 24:23 \ft ﻿*Here this participle (“ordered”) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style \ef* the centurion \add for\add* him to be guarded and to have some freedom, and in no way to prevent any of his own \add people\add*\f + \fr 24:23 \ft This could refer to either friends or relatives \f* \add from\add* serving him.
\p 
\v 24 And after some days, \add when\add*\ef + \fr 24:24 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“arrived”) which is understood as temporal \ef* Felix arrived with his wife Drusilla, who was Jewish, he sent for Paul and listened to him concerning faith in Christ Jesus. 
\v 25 And \add while\add*\ef + \fr 24:25 \ft ﻿*Here “\add while\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“was discussing”) \ef* he was discussing about righteousness and self control and the judgment that is to come, Felix became afraid \add and\add*\ef + \fr 24:25 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“became”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* replied, “Go away for the present, and \add when I\add*\ef + \fr 24:25 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“have”) which is understood as temporal \ef* have an opportunity, I will summon you.” 
\v 26 At the same time he was also hoping that money would be given to him by Paul. For this reason also he sent for him as often as possible \add and\add*\ef + \fr 24:26 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“sent for”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* talked with him. 
\v 27 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 24:27 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“had passed”) \ef* two years had passed, Felix received as successor Porcius Festus. And \add because he\add*\ef + \fr 24:27 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“wanted”) which is understood as causal \ef* wanted to do a favor for the Jews, Felix left Paul behind ⸤as a prisoner⸥.\f + \fr 24:27 \ft Literally “bound” \f*
\c 25
\s1 Paul Appeals to Caesar
\m 
\v 1  Now \add when\add*\ef + \fr 25:1 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“set foot in”) which is understood as temporal \ef* Festus set foot in the province, after three days he went up to Jerusalem from Caesarea. 
\v 2 And the chief priests and the most prominent men of the Jews brought charges against Paul to him, and were urging him, 
\v 3 asking for a favor against him, that he summon him to Jerusalem, \add because they\add*\ef + \fr 25:3 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“were preparing ”) which is understood as causal \ef* were preparing an ambush to do away with him along the way. 
\v 4 Then Festus replied \add that\add* Paul was being kept at Caesarea, and \add he\add* himself was about to go \add there\add*\ef + \fr 25:4 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* in a short time. 
\v 5 So he said, “Let those among you \add who are\add* prominent go down with \add me\add*,\ef + \fr 25:5 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* \add and\add*\ef + \fr 25:5 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“go down with”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* if there is any wrong in the man, let them bring charges against him.”
\p 
\v 6 And \add after he\add*\ef + \fr 25:6 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“had stayed”) which is understood as temporal \ef* had stayed among them not more than eight or ten days, he went down to Caesarea. On the next day he sat down on the judgment seat \add and\add*\ef + \fr 25:6 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“sat down”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* gave orders \add for\add* Paul to be brought. 
\v 7 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 25:7 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“arrived”) \ef* he arrived, the Jews who had come down from Jerusalem stood around him, bringing many and serious charges that they were not able to prove, 
\v 8 \add while\add*\ef + \fr 25:8 \ft ﻿*Here “\add while\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“said in his defense”) \ef* Paul said in his defense, “Neither against the law of the Jews nor against the temple nor against Caesar have I sinned with reference to anything!” 
\v 9 But Festus, \add because he\add*\ef + \fr 25:9 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“wanted”) which is understood as causal \ef* wanted to do a favor for the Jews, answered \add and\add*\ef + \fr 25:9 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“answered”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* said to Paul, “Are you willing to go up to Jerusalem to be tried before me there concerning these \add things\add*?” 
\v 10 But Paul said, “I am standing before the judgment seat of Caesar, where it is necessary \add for\add* me to be judged. I have done no wrong to the Jews, as you also know very well. 
\v 11 If then I am doing wrong\f + \fr 25:11 \ft Or “I am in the wrong” \f* and have done anything deserving death, I am not trying to avoid\ef + \fr 25:11 \ft ﻿*Here the present tense has been translated as conative (“trying to avoid”) \ef* dying. But if there is nothing \add true\add* of \add the things\add* which these \add people\add* are accusing me, no one can give me up to them. I appeal to Caesar!” 
\v 12 Then Festus, \add after\add*\ef + \fr 25:12 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“discussing”) which is understood as temporal \ef* discussing \add this\add*\ef + \fr 25:12 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* with \add his\add*\ef + \fr 25:12 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* council, replied, “You have appealed to Caesar—to Caesar you will go!”
\s1 Festus Asks King Agrippa for Advice
\m 
\v 13 Now \add after\add*\ef + \fr 25:13 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“had passed”) \ef* some days had passed, King Agrippa and Bernice arrived at Caesarea to welcome Festus. 
\v 14 And while they were staying there many days, Festus laid out the \add case\add* against Paul to the king, saying, “There is a certain man left behind by Felix \add as\add* a prisoner, 
\v 15 concerning whom \add when\add*\ef + \fr 25:15 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“was”) \ef* I was in Jerusalem the chief priests and the elders of the Jews presented evidence, asking for a sentence of condemnation against him. 
\v 16 To ⸤them⸥\f + \fr 25:16 \ft Literally “whom” \f* I replied that it was not the custom of the Romans to give up any man before the one who had been accused met \add his\add*\ef + \fr 25:16 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* accusers face to \add face\add* and received an opportunity for a defense concerning the accusation. 
\v 17 Therefore, \add when\add*\ef + \fr 25:17 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“had assembled”) \ef* they had assembled here, \add I\add* made\ef + \fr 25:17 \ft ﻿*Here this participle (“made”) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style \ef* no delay; on the next \add day\add* I sat down on the judgment seat \add and\add*\ef + \fr 25:17 \ft ﻿*Here “and” is supplied because the two previous participles (“made” and “sat down”) have been translated as finite verbs \ef* gave orders \add for\add* the man to be brought. 
\v 18 \add When they\add*\ef + \fr 25:18 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“stood up”) which is understood as temporal \ef* stood up, \add his\add*\ef + \fr 25:18 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* accusers began bringing\ef + \fr 25:18 \ft ﻿*The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (“began bringing”) \ef* no charge concerning ⸤him⸥\f + \fr 25:18 \ft Literally “whom” \f* of the evil deeds that I was suspecting, 
\v 19 but they had some issues with him concerning their own religion, and concerning a certain Jesus, who was dead, whom Paul claimed to be alive. 
\v 20 And \add because\add*\ef + \fr 25:20 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“was at a loss”) which is understood as causal \ef* I was at a loss with regard to the investigation concerning these \add things\add*, I asked if he was willing to go to Jerusalem and to be judged there concerning these \add things\add*. 
\v 21 But \add when\add*\ef + \fr 25:21 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“appealed”) \ef* Paul appealed \add that\add* he be kept under guard for the decision of His Majesty the Emperor, I gave orders \add for\add* him to be kept under guard until I could send him to Caesar.” 
\v 22 So Agrippa \add said\add* to Festus, “I want to hear the man myself also.” “Tomorrow,” he said, “you will hear him.”
\p 
\v 23 So on the next day, Agrippa and Bernice came with great pageantry and entered into the audience hall, along with military tribunes and the most prominent men of the city. And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 25:23 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“gave the order”) \ef* Festus gave the order, Paul was brought in. 
\v 24 And Festus said, “King Agrippa and all who are present with us, you see this man about whom the whole population of the Jews appealed to me, both in Jerusalem and here, shouting \add that\add* he must not live any longer. 
\v 25 But I understood \add that\add* he had done nothing deserving death himself, and \add when\add*\ef + \fr 25:25 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“appealed to”) \ef* this man appealed to His Majesty the Emperor, I decided to send \add him\add*.\ef + \fr 25:25 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* 
\v 26 I do not have anything definite to write to \add my\add*\ef + \fr 25:26 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* lord about ⸤him⸥.\f + \fr 25:26 \ft Literally “whom” \f* Therefore I have brought him before you \add all\add*\ef + \fr 25:26 \ft ﻿*Here “\add all\add*” is supplied in the translation to indicate that the pronoun (“you”) is plural \ef*—and especially before you, King Agrippa—so that \add after\add*\ef + \fr 25:26 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“has taken place”) \ef* this preliminary hearing has taken place, I may have something to write. 
\v 27 For it seems unreasonable to me to send a prisoner and not to indicate the charges against him.”
\c 26
\s1 Paul Makes His Defense Before King Agrippa
\m 
\v 1  So Agrippa said to Paul, “It is permitted for you to speak for yourself.” Then Paul extended \add his\add*\ef + \fr 26:1 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* hand \add and\add*\ef + \fr 26:1 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“extended”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* began to defend himself:\ef + \fr 26:1 \ft *The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (“began to defend himself”) \ef*
\p 
\v 2 “Concerning all \add the things\add* of which I am accused by the Jews, King Agrippa, I consider myself fortunate \add that\add* before you I am about to defend myself today, 
\v 3 \add because\add*\ef + \fr 26:3 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“are”) which is understood as causal \ef* you are especially acquainted with both all the customs and controversial questions with respect to the Jews. Therefore I beg \add you\add*\ef + \fr 26:3 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* to listen to me with patience.
\p 
\v 4 “Now all the Jews know my manner of life from \add my\add* youth, that had taken place from the beginning among my \add own\add* people\f + \fr 26:4 \ft Or “nation” \f* and in Jerusalem, 
\v 5 having known me for a long time, if they are willing to testify, that in accordance with the strictest party of our religion I lived \add as\add* a Pharisee. 
\v 6 And now I stand here on trial on the basis of hope in the promise made by God to our fathers, 
\v 7 to which our twelve tribes hope to attain as \add they\add* earnestly serve \add him\add*\ef + \fr 26:7 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* night and day. Concerning this hope I am being accused by the Jews, O king! 
\v 8 Why is it thought incredible by you \add people\add*\ef + \fr 26:8 \ft ﻿*Here “people” is supplied in the translation to indicate that the pronoun (“you”) is plural \ef* that God raises the dead? 
\v 9 Indeed, I myself thought it was necessary to do many \add things\add* opposed to the name of Jesus the Nazarene, 
\v 10 which I also did in Jerusalem, and not only did I lock up many of the saints in prison, having received authority from the chief priests, but also \add when\add*\ef + \fr 26:10 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“were being executed”) \ef* they were being executed, I cast \add my\add* vote\f + \fr 26:10 \ft Literally “voting pebble,” but here “vote” rather than “voting pebble” is used in the translation to avoid the idea that this small stone was actually thrown at the accused (it was used as a method of voting) \f* against \add them\add*.\ef + \fr 26:10 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* 
\v 11 And throughout all the synagogues I punished them often \add and\add*\ef + \fr 26:11 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“punished”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* tried to force\ef + \fr 26:11 \ft ﻿*The imperfect tense has been translated as conative here (“tried to force”) \ef* \add them\add*\ef + \fr 26:11 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* to blaspheme, and \add because I\add*\ef + \fr 26:11 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“was enraged”) which is understood as causal \ef* was enraged at them beyond measure, I was pursuing \add them\add*\ef + \fr 26:11 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* even as far as to foreign cities. 
\v 12 In ⸤this activity⸥\f + \fr 26:12 \ft Literally “which” \f* I was traveling to Damascus with the authority and full power of the chief priests. 
\v 13 In the middle of the day along the road, O king, I saw a light from heaven, more than the brightness of the sun, shining around me and those who were traveling with me. 
\v 14 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 26:14 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“had … fallen”) \ef* we had all fallen to the ground, I heard a voice saying to me in the Aramaic language, ‘Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me? \add It is\add* hard for you to kick against the goads!’ 
\v 15 So I said, ‘Who are you, Lord?’ And the Lord said, ‘I am Jesus whom you are persecuting. 
\v 16 But get up and stand on your feet, because for this \add reason\add* I have appeared to you, to appoint you a servant and witness both \add to the things\add* in which you saw me and \add to the things\add* in which I will appear to you, 
\v 17 rescuing you from the people and from the Gentiles to whom I am sending you, 
\v 18 to open their eyes \add so that they\add* may turn from darkness to light and from the power of Satan to God, \add so that\add* they may receive forgiveness of sins and a share among those who are sanctified by faith in me.’
\p 
\v 19 “Therefore, O King Agrippa, I was not disobedient to the heavenly vision, 
\v 20 but to those in Damascus first, and in Jerusalem and all the region of Judea and to the Gentiles, I proclaimed \add that they should\add* repent and turn to God, doing deeds worthy of repentance. 
\v 21 On account of these \add things\add* the Jews seized me in\f + \fr 26:21 \ft Some manuscripts have “while I was in” \f* the temple \add courts\add*\ef + \fr 26:21 \ft ﻿*Here “\add courts\add*” is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself \ef* \add and\add*\ef + \fr 26:21 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“seized”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* were attempting to kill \add me\add*.\ef + \fr 26:21 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* 
\v 22 Therefore I have experienced help from God until this day, \add and\add*\ef + \fr 26:22 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“have experienced”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* I stand here testifying to both small and great, saying nothing except what both the prophets and Moses have said were going to happen, 
\v 23 that the Christ\f + \fr 26:23 \ft Or “Messiah” \f* was to suffer \add and\add* that \add as\add* the first of the resurrection from the dead, he was going to proclaim light both to the people and to the Gentiles.”
\p 
\v 24 And \add as\add*\ef + \fr 26:24 \ft ﻿*Here “\add as\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“was saying … in his defense”) \ef* he was saying these things in his defense, Festus said with a loud voice, “You are out of your mind, Paul! \add Your\add*\ef + \fr 26:24 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* great learning ⸤is driving⸥\f + \fr 26:24 \ft Literally “is turning” \f* you ⸤insane⸥!”\f + \fr 26:24 \ft Literally “to madness” \f* 
\v 25 But Paul said, “I am not out of my mind, most excellent Festus, but am speaking words of truth and rationality. 
\v 26 For the king knows about these \add things\add*, to whom also I am speaking freely, for I am not convinced \add that\add* these \add things\add* in any way have escaped\f + \fr 26:26 \ft Some manuscripts have “that any of these \fq things \ft in any way has escaped” \f* his notice, because this ⸤was⸥\f + \fr 26:26 \ft Literally “is” \f* not ⸤done⸥\f + \fr 26:26 \ft Literally “having been done” \f* in a corner. 
\v 27 Do you believe the prophets, King Agrippa? I know that you believe.” 
\v 28 But Agrippa \add said\add* to Paul, “In a short time are you persuading me to become a Christian?”\f + \fr 26:28 \ft Or “In a short time you are persuading me to become a Christian” \f* 
\v 29 And Paul \add replied\add*, “I pray to God, whether in a short time or in a long time, not only you but also all those who are listening to me today may become such \add people\add* as I also am, except for these bonds!”
\p 
\v 30 Both the king and the governor got up, and Bernice and those who were sitting with them. 
\v 31 And \add as they\add*\ef + \fr 26:31 \ft ﻿*Here “\add as\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“were going out”) \ef* were going out, they were talking to one another, saying, “This man is not doing anything deserving death or imprisonment.” 
\v 32 And Agrippa said to Festus, “This man could have been released if he had not appealed to Caesar.”
\c 27
\s1 Paul and His Associates Sail for Rome
\m 
\v 1  And when it was decided \add that\add* we would sail away to Italy, they handed over Paul and some other prisoners to a centurion ⸤named⸥\f + \fr 27:1 \ft Literally “by name” \f* Julius of the Augustan\f + \fr 27:1 \ft The meaning and significance of the title “Augustan” is highly debated, as is the precise identification of this military unit; it may be an honorary unit designation given to auxiliary or provincial troops \f* Cohort. 
\v 2 And we went aboard a ship from Adramyttium that was about to sail to the places along the \add coast\add*\ef + \fr 27:2 \ft ﻿*The word “\add coast\add*” is not in the Greek text but is implied \ef* of Asia\f + \fr 27:2 \ft A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor) \f* \add and\add*\ef + \fr 27:2 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“went aboard”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* put out to sea. Aristarchus, a Macedonian from Thessalonica, was with us. 
\v 3 And on the next \add day\add*, we put in at Sidon. And Julius, treating Paul kindly, allowed \add him\add*\ef + \fr 27:3 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* to go to \add his\add*\ef + \fr 27:3 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* friends ⸤to be cared for⸥.\f + \fr 27:3 \ft Literally “to experience care” \f* 
\v 4 And from there we put out to sea \add and\add*\ef + \fr 27:4 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“put out to sea”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* sailed under the lee of Cyprus, because the winds were against \add us\add*.\ef + \fr 27:4 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* 
\v 5 And \add after we\add*\ef + \fr 27:5 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“had sailed across”) which is understood as temporal \ef* had sailed across the open sea along Cilicia and Pamphylia, we put in at Myra in Lycia. 
\v 6 And there the centurion found an Alexandrian ship sailing for Italy \add and\add*\ef + \fr 27:6 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“found”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* put us ⸤on board⸥\f + \fr 27:6 \ft Literally “into” \f* it. 
\v 7 And sailing slowly, in many days and with difficulty we came\ef + \fr 27:7 \ft ﻿*Here this participle (“came”) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style \ef* to Cnidus. \add Because\add*\ef + \fr 27:7 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (“permit … to go further”) \ef* the wind did not permit us to go further, we sailed under the lee of Crete off Salmone. 
\v 8 And sailing along its coast with difficulty, we came to a certain place called Fair Havens, near which was the town \add of\add* Lasea.
\p 
\v 9 And \add because\add*\ef + \fr 27:9 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (“had passed”) \ef* considerable time had passed and the voyage was now dangerous because even the Fast\f + \fr 27:9 \ft A reference to the Jewish Day of Atonement (Yom Kippur) which occurs in mid-autumn \f* was already over, Paul strongly recommended, 
\v 10 saying to them, “Men, I perceive that the voyage is going ⸤to end⸥\f + \fr 27:10 \ft Literally “to be” \f* with disaster and great loss, not only of the cargo and the ship, but also of our lives!” 
\v 11 But the centurion was convinced even more by the shipmaster and the shipowner than by what was said by Paul. 
\v 12 And \add because\add*\ef + \fr 27:12 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (“was”) \ef* the harbor was unsuitable for spending the winter in, the majority decided on a plan to put out to sea from there, if somehow they could arrive at Phoenix, a harbor of Crete facing toward the southwest and toward the northwest, to spend the winter \add there\add*.\ef + \fr 27:12 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef*
\s1 A Violent Storm at Sea
\m 
\v 13 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 27:13 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“began to blow gently”) \ef* a southwest wind began to blow gently, \add because they\add*\ef + \fr 27:13 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“thought”) which is understood as causal \ef* thought \add they\add* could accomplish their purpose, they weighed anchor \add and\add*\ef + \fr 27:13 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“weighed anchor”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* sailed close along Crete. 
\v 14 But not long afterward a wind like a hurricane, called the northeaster,\f + \fr 27:14 \ft Literally “Euraquilo,” a violent northern wind \f* rushed down from it.\f + \fr 27:14 \ft That is, from the island of Crete \f* 
\v 15 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 27:15 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“was caught”) \ef* the ship was caught and \add was\add* not able to head into the wind, we gave way \add and\add*\ef + \fr 27:15 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“gave way”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* were driven \add along\add*. 
\v 16 And running under the lee of a certain small island called Cauda, we were able with difficulty to get the ship’s boat under control. 
\v 17 \add After\add*\ef + \fr 27:17 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“hoisting”) which is understood as temporal \ef* hoisting ⸤it up⸥,\f + \fr 27:17 \ft Literally “which” \f* they made use of supports to undergird the ship. And \add because they\add*\ef + \fr 27:17 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“were afraid”) which is understood as causal \ef* were afraid lest they run aground on the Syrtis, they lowered the sea anchor \add and\add*\ef + \fr 27:17 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“lowered”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* thus were driven \add along\add*. 
\v 18 And \add because\add*\ef + \fr 27:18 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (“battered by the storm”) \ef* we were violently battered by the storm, on the next \add day\add* ⸤they began⸥\f + \fr 27:18 \ft Literally “they began to carry out” \f* jettisoning \add the cargo\add*,\ef + \fr 27:18 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* 
\v 19 and on the third \add day\add* they threw overboard the gear of the ship with their own hands. 
\v 20 But \add when\add*\ef + \fr 27:20 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“appeared”) \ef* neither sun nor stars appeared for many days, and \add with\add* not a little bad weather confronting \add us\add*,\ef + \fr 27:20 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* finally all hope was abandoned \add that\add* we would be saved.
\p 
\v 21 And \add because\add*\ef + \fr 27:21 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (“were experiencing”) \ef* many were experiencing lack of appetite, at that time Paul stood up in their midst \add and\add*\ef + \fr 27:21 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“stood up”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* said, “Men, \add you\add* ought to have followed my \add advice\add* not to put out to sea from Crete, and \add thus\add* avoided this damage and loss! 
\v 22 And now I urge you to cheer up, for there will be no loss of life from among you, but only of the ship. 
\v 23 For this night an angel of the God whose I am and whom I serve came to me, 
\v 24 saying, ‘Do not be afraid, Paul! It is necessary \add for\add* you to stand before Caesar, and behold, God has graciously granted you all who are sailing with you.’ 
\v 25 Therefore keep up your courage, men, for I believe God that it will be like this—according to ⸤the⸥\f + \fr 27:25 \ft Literally “which” \f* way it was told to me. 
\v 26 But it is necessary \add that\add* we run aground on some island.”
\p 
\v 27 And when the fourteenth night had come, \add as\add*\ef + \fr 27:27 \ft ﻿*Here “\add as\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“were being driven”) \ef* we were being driven in the Adriatic Sea about the middle of the night, the sailors suspected ⸤they were approaching some land⸥.\f + \fr 27:27 \ft Literally “some land was approaching them” \f* 
\v 28 And taking soundings, they found twenty fathoms. So going on a little \add further\add* and taking soundings again, they found fifteen fathoms. 
\v 29 And \add because they\add*\ef + \fr 27:29 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“were afraid”) which is understood as causal \ef* were afraid lest somewhere we run aground against rough places, they threw down four anchors from the stern \add and\add*\ef + \fr 27:29 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“threw down”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* prayed for day to come. 
\v 30 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 27:30 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“were seeking”) \ef* the sailors were seeking to escape from the ship and were lowering the ship’s boat into the sea, pretending as if they were going to lay out anchors from the bow, 
\v 31 Paul said to the centurion and the soldiers, “Unless these \add men\add* remain with the ship, you cannot be saved!” 
\v 32 Then the soldiers cut away the ropes of the ship’s boat and let it fall away.\f + \fr 27:32 \ft Or “let it drift away” \f*
\p 
\v 33 And until the day was about to come, Paul was urging \add them\add* all to take \add some\add* food, saying, “Today \add is the\add* fourteenth day you have waited \add anxiously\add*, \add and\add*\ef + \fr 27:33 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“have waited”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* you have continued without eating, having taken nothing. 
\v 34 Therefore I urge you to take \add some\add* food, for this is necessary for your preservation. For not a hair from your head will be lost.” 
\v 35 And \add after he\add*\ef + \fr 27:35 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“said”) which is understood as temporal \ef* said these \add things\add* and took bread, he gave thanks to God in front of \add them\add* all, and \add after\add*\ef + \fr 27:35 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“breaking”) which is understood as temporal \ef* breaking \add it\add*,\ef + \fr 27:35 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* he began to eat. 
\v 36 So they all were\ef + \fr 27:36 \ft ﻿*Here this participle (“were”) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style \ef* encouraged and partook of food themselves. 
\v 37 (Now we were \add in\add* all two hundred seventy six persons on the ship.) 
\v 38 And \add when they\add*\ef + \fr 27:38 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“had eaten their fill”) which is understood as temporal \ef* had eaten their fill of food, they lightened the ship \add by\add*\ef + \fr 27:38 \ft ﻿*Here “\add by\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“throwing”) which is understood as means \ef* throwing the wheat\f + \fr 27:38 \ft Or “grain” \f* into the sea.
\s1 The Shipwreck
\m 
\v 39 Now when day came, they did not recognize the land, but they noticed a certain bay having a beach, onto which they decided to run the ship ashore if they could. 
\v 40 And slipping the anchors, they left \add them\add*\ef + \fr 27:40 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* in the sea, at the same time loosening the ropes\f + \fr 27:40 \ft Or “bands” (referring to the linkage that tied the steering oars together) \f* of the steering oars. And hoisting the foresail to the \add wind\add* that was blowing, they held course for the beach. 
\v 41 But falling into a place of crosscurrents,\f + \fr 27:41 \ft Or “a reef”; literally “a place of two seas,” an expression of uncertain meaning but most likely a nautical technical term for some adverse sea condition \f* they ran the ship aground. And the bow stuck fast \add and\add*\ef + \fr 27:41 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“stuck fast”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* stayed immovable, but the stern was being broken up by the violence.\f + \fr 27:41 \ft Some manuscripts have “the violence of the waves” \f* 
\v 42 Now the plan of the soldiers was that they would kill the prisoners lest any escape \add by\add*\ef + \fr 27:42 \ft ﻿*Here “\add by\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“swimming away”) which is understood as means \ef* swimming away, 
\v 43 but the centurion, \add because he\add*\ef + \fr 27:43 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“wanted”) which is understood as causal \ef* wanted to save Paul, prevented them ⸤from doing what they intended⸥,\f + \fr 27:43 \ft Literally “of the intention” \f* and gave orders \add that\add* those who were able to swim should jump in first to get to the land, 
\v 44 and \add then\add* the rest, \add some\add* of whom \add floated\add*\ef + \fr 27:44 \ft ﻿*The word “\add floated\add*” is not in the Greek text, but is supplied in the translation for clarity \ef* on planks and \add some\add* of whom on anything \add that was\add* from the ship. And in this way all were brought safely to the land.
\c 28
\s1 Paul on Malta
\m 
\v 1  And \add after we\add*\ef + \fr 28:1 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“were brought safely through”) which is understood as temporal \ef* were brought safely through, then we found out that the island was called Malta. 
\v 2 And the local inhabitants showed ⸤extraordinary⸥\f + \fr 28:2 \ft Literally “not the ordinary” \f* kindness to us, for they lit a fire \add and\add*\ef + \fr 28:2 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“lit”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* welcomed us all, because of the rain that had begun and because of the cold. 
\v 3 And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 28:3 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“had gathered”) \ef* Paul had gathered a large number of sticks and was placing \add them\add*\ef + \fr 28:3 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* on the fire, a viper came out because of the heat \add and\add*\ef + \fr 28:3 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“came out”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* fastened itself on his hand. 
\v 4 And when the local people saw the creature hanging from his hand, they began saying\ef + \fr 28:4 \ft ﻿*The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (“began saying”) \ef* to one another, “Doubtless this man is a murderer whom, \add although he\add*\ef + \fr 28:4 \ft ﻿*Here “\add although\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“was rescued”) which is understood as concessive \ef* was rescued from the sea, Justice\ef + \fr 28:4 \ft ﻿*Here personified as a goddess \ef* has not permitted to live!” 
\v 5 He, in turn, shook off the creature into the fire \add and\add*\ef + \fr 28:5 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“shook off”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* suffered no harm. 
\v 6 But they were expecting \add that\add* he was going to swell up\f + \fr 28:6 \ft Or “to burn with fever” (either meaning is possible here) \f* or suddenly to fall down dead. So \add after\add*\ef + \fr 28:6 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“had waited”) \ef* they had waited for a long \add time\add* and saw nothing unusual happen to him, they changed their minds \add and\add*\ef + \fr 28:6 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“changed their minds”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* began saying\ef + \fr 28:6 \ft ﻿*The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (“began saying”) \ef* \add that\add* he was a god.
\p 
\v 7 Now in the \add regions\add* around that place were fields belonging to the chief official of the island, ⸤named⸥\f + \fr 28:7 \ft Literally “by name” \f* Publius, who welcomed us \add and\add*\ef + \fr 28:7 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“welcomed”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* entertained \add us\add*\ef + \fr 28:7 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* hospitably \add for\add* three days. 
\v 8 And it happened that the father of Publius was lying down, afflicted with fever and dysentery. Paul went\ef + \fr 28:8 \ft ﻿*Here this participle (“went”) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style \ef* to ⸤him⸥\f + \fr 28:8 \ft Literally “whom” \f* and \add after\add*\ef + \fr 28:8 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“praying”) which is understood as temporal \ef* praying, he placed \add his\add*\ef + \fr 28:8 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* hands on him \add and\add*\ef + \fr 28:8 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“placed”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* healed him. 
\v 9 And \add after\add*\ef + \fr 28:9 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“had taken place”) \ef* this had taken place, the rest of those on the island who had diseases were coming and being healed also. 
\v 10 They also honored us with many honors, and \add when we\add*\ef + \fr 28:10 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“putting out to sea”) which is understood as temporal \ef* were putting out to sea, they gave \add us\add*\ef + \fr 28:10 \ft ﻿*Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* the \add things\add* ⸤we needed⸥.\f + \fr 28:10 \ft Literally “for the needs” \f*
\s1 Paul Arrives in Rome at Last
\m 
\v 11 Now after three months we put out to sea in a ship that had wintered at the island, an Alexandrian \add one\add* ⸤with the twin gods Castor and Pollux as its insignia⸥.\f + \fr 28:11 \ft Literally “marked with the Dioscuri” (a joint name for the twin gods Castor and Pollux) \f* 
\v 12 And putting in at Syracuse, we stayed \add there\add* three days. 
\v 13 From there we got underway\f + \fr 28:13 \ft Or “we sailed along” (with “the coast” understood); the exact meaning of the text as it stands is disputed and various additional terms have to be supplied in any case \f* \add and\add*\ef + \fr 28:13 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“got underway”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* arrived at Rhegium, and after one day a south wind came up \add and\add*\ef + \fr 28:13 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“came up”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* on the second day we came to Puteoli, 
\v 14 where we found brothers, \add and\add*\ef + \fr 28:14 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“found”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* were implored to stay with them seven days. And in this way we came to Rome. 
\v 15 And from there the brothers, \add when they\add*\ef + \fr 28:15 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“heard”) which is understood as temporal \ef* heard the \add news\add* about us, came to meet us as far as the Forum of Appius and Three Taverns. \add When he\add*\ef + \fr 28:15 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“saw”) which is understood as temporal \ef* saw them, Paul gave thanks to God \add and\add*\ef + \fr 28:15 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“gave thanks”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* took courage. 
\v 16 And when we entered into Rome, Paul was allowed to stay by himself with the soldier who was guarding him.
\s1 Paul and the Jewish Community in Rome
\m 
\v 17 Now it happened that after three days, he called together those who were the most prominent of the Jews. And \add when\add*\ef + \fr 28:17 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“had assembled”) \ef* they had assembled, he said to them, “Men \add and\add* brothers, \add although\add*\ef + \fr 28:17 \ft ﻿*Here “\add although\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“had done”) which is understood as concessive \ef* I had done nothing against \add our\add*\ef + \fr 28:17 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* people or the customs of our fathers, from Jerusalem I was delivered \add as\add* a prisoner into the hands of the Romans, 
\v 18 who, \add when they\add*\ef + \fr 28:18 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“had examined”) which is understood as temporal \ef* had examined me, were wanting to release \add me\add*,\ef + \fr 28:18 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* because there was no basis for an accusation \add worthy\add* of death with me. 
\v 19 But \add because\add*\ef + \fr 28:19 \ft ﻿*Here “\add because\add*” is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (“objected”) \ef* the Jews objected, I was forced to appeal to Caesar (not as \add if I\add*\ef + \fr 28:19 \ft ﻿*Here “\add if\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“had”) which is understood as concessive \ef* had any \add charge\add* to bring against my \add own\add* people).\f + \fr 28:19 \ft Or “nation” \f* 
\v 20 Therefore for this reason I have requested to see you and to speak with \add you\add*,\ef + \fr 28:20 \ft *Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation \ef* for because of the hope of Israel I am wearing this chain!” 
\v 21 And they said to him, “We have received no letters about you from Judea, nor has any of the brothers come \add and\add*\ef + \fr 28:21 \ft ﻿*Here “\add and\add*” is supplied because the previous participle (“come”) has been translated as a finite verb \ef* reported or spoken anything evil about you. 
\v 22 But we would like to hear from you what you think, for concerning this sect it is known to us that it is spoken against everywhere.”
\p 
\v 23 And \add when they\add*\ef + \fr 28:23 \ft ﻿*Here “\add when\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“had set”) which is understood as temporal \ef* had set a day with him, many more came to him at his lodging place, to whom he was explaining from early in the morning until evening, testifying about the kingdom of God and attempting to convince\ef + \fr 28:23 \ft ﻿*Here the present tense has been translated as conative (“attempting to convince”) \ef* them about Jesus from both the law of Moses and the prophets. 
\v 24 And \add some\add* were convinced \add by\add*\ef + \fr 28:24 \ft ﻿*Here “\add by\add*” is supplied as a component of the participle (“what was said”) which is understood as means \ef* what was said, but \add others\add* refused to believe. 
\v 25 So being in disagreement with one another, they began to leave \add after\add*\ef + \fr 28:25 \ft ﻿*Here “\add after\add*” is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (“made”) \ef* Paul made one statement: “The Holy Spirit spoke rightly through the prophet Isaiah to your fathers, 
\v 26 saying,
