\q1 ‘Go to this people and say,
\q2 “⸤You will keep on hearing⸥\f + \fr 28:26 \ft Literally “hearing you will hear” \f* and will never understand,
\q1 and ⸤you will keep on seeing⸥\f + \fr 28:26 \ft Literally “seeing you will see” \f* and will never perceive.
\q2 
\v 27 For the heart of this people has become dull,
\q1 and with \add their\add*\ef + \fr 28:27 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* ears they hear with difficulty,
\q2 and they have shut their eyes,
\q1 lest they see with \add their\add*\ef + \fr 28:27 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* eyes,
\q2 and hear with \add their\add*\ef + \fr 28:27 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* ears,
\q2 and understand with \add their\add*\ef + \fr 28:27 \ft ﻿*Literally “the”; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun \ef* heart,
\q1 and turn, and I would heal them.” ’\f + \fr 28:27 \ft A quotation from \xt Isa 6:9–10 \ft \f*
\sd0
\p 
\v 28 Therefore let it be known to you that this salvation of God has been sent to the Gentiles. They also will listen!”\f + \fr 28:28 \ft Some later manuscripts include v. \xt 29 \ft : “And when he had said these things, the Jews departed, having a great dispute among themselves.” \f*
\p 
\v 30 So he stayed two whole years in his own rented house, and welcomed all who came to him, 
\v 31 proclaiming the kingdom of God and teaching the \add things\add* concerning the Lord Jesus Christ with all boldness, without hindrance.
